{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/quick-forecasting-with-facebook-prophet-under-10-lines-of-code-4b23df30e517", "time": 1683013261.580493, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/quick-forecasting-with-facebook-prophet-under-10-lines-of-code-4b23df30e517/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Quick forecasting with Facebook Prophet \u2014 under 10 lines of code | by Mahbubul Alam | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Quick forecasting with Facebook Prophet \u2014 under 10 lines of code", "description": "I used to use Rob J Hyndman\u2019s fpp2 forecasting package. Quite a lot. Still it\u2019s my go-to forecasting library. The reason I like it so much is that it comes with extensive coverage of forecasting\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/fpp2/index.html", "anchor_text": "Rob J Hyndman\u2019s", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/fpp2/index.html", "anchor_text": "fpp2", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/fpp2/index.html", "anchor_text": "forecasting package", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://otexts.com/fpp2/", "anchor_text": "open access book", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://scikit-learn.org/stable/", "anchor_text": "Scikit Learn", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://facebook.github.io/prophet/docs/quick_start.html", "anchor_text": "documentation", "paragraph_index": 20}, {"url": "https://twitter.com/home", "anchor_text": "Twitter", "paragraph_index": 22}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/mab-alam/", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 22}], "all_paragraphs": ["I used to use Rob J Hyndman\u2019s fpp2 forecasting package. Quite a lot. Still it\u2019s my go-to forecasting library. The reason I like it so much is that it comes with extensive coverage of forecasting techniques and an invaluable open access book that has all the theories going into forecasting. Pretty much everything you need for academic research on time series is there.", "But that\u2019s also the downside of the package, it\u2019s not beginner-friendly. Who wants to build a car just to drive it on the road?", "Prophet made unbelievable simplification to forecasting exercise. You can use it out of the box without needing to understand a lot of theories, as you are about to see below.", "The package is very intuitive to use and is especially powerful for business forecasting. You can even specify weekends, special days and events (e.g. Superbowl) that impact business activities.", "Cherry on top, Prophet is available in both python and R programming language!", "I\u2019m doing it in Python, so all you need is pandas package for manipulating data.", "The dataset I\u2019m going to use is a time series consisting of daily minimum temperature recorded for 10 years between 1981 and 1990.", "As you can see, the datarame has just two columns, one on the time dimension and the other on observations.", "Some data formatting is needed. Prophet requires that the datetime column is named as \u201cds\u201d and the observation column as \u201cy\u201d.", "Similar to Scikit Learn algorithms, Prophet follows a simple \u201cinstantiate \u2192 fit \u2192 predict\u201d workflow for forecasting.", "You can play with parameters but for building your first forecasting model out of the box package, it is as simple as those two tiny lines of code.", "Now that you\u2019ve your model, you are ready to make a forecast.", "Just like building the model, forecasting is also a two-lines code. In the first line, you make an empty dataframe to store forecast values. In the second line you pass in the empty dataframe into the model, the model will fill out the rows with predicted values.", "You are done with forecasting, you can now check out the forecast values in a dataframe.", "The column names are intuitive \u2014", "It\u2019s always good to visualize data and forecast values altogether to see how they fit.", "Again, it\u2019s just a one-liner code.", "In this figure below, each black dot represents the original observations, the dark green line is forecast model and the light green line is confidence intervals.", "There! You made a real forecasting model under 10 lines of code!", "In this article I didn\u2019t mean to go deep into the model, the purpose was rather to convince people that it\u2019s not complicated to build a forecasting model, even if you know little about theories.", "As a next step, you can explore other functionalities \u2014 they have a very easy-to-follow documentation. I would specifically encourage folks to explore how special days and events affect forecasting (not temperature of course! but business activities).", "As I said, you can implement the package both in Python and R programming environment, so that gives you some extra freedom.", "Feel free to follow me on Twitter or LinkedIn.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F4b23df30e517&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fquick-forecasting-with-facebook-prophet-under-10-lines-of-code-4b23df30e517&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fquick-forecasting-with-facebook-prophet-under-10-lines-of-code-4b23df30e517&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=r